                            <comment id="19667" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 15 Sep 2006 02:06:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Note that Spring does &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; use EHCache itself at all, unless you happen to use it within your application (and might use Spring&apos;s EhCacheManagerFactoryBean to set up a CacheManager). Hence, please double-check your application&apos;s Hibernate configuration and potential direct use of EHCache!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19679" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sat, 16 Sep 2006 02:43:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;After some clarification from the EHCache and Acegi guys, I learned that EHCache 1.2 introduced public constructors on the CacheManager, to allow for independent CacheManager instances. It should have done that long ago, IMO, but better late than never &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/wink.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While the singleton factory methods still work, it seems that Hibernate 3.2 is now using independent CacheManager instances. To play nicely alongside this, I&apos;ve refined Spring&apos;s EhCacheManagerFactoryBean to create independent CacheManager by default as well. Note that this only kicks in when your application actually uses EhCacheManagerFactoryBean, since Spring does &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; use EHCache itself. However, Acegi Security is often used with EhCacheManagerFactoryBean, so this new default for EHCache 1.2 certainly makes sense.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
